---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import LocalDimming from '../components/benchmarks/LocalDimming.tsx';

const title = "Local Dimming & Blooming Test";
const description = "Test Full Array Local Dimming (FALD) and Mini-LED displays for blooming/halo artifacts around bright objects.";

const jsonLd = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "WebApplication",
  "name": title,
  "url": "https://screenhz.com/local-dimming",
  "description": description,
  "applicationCategory": "UtilitiesApplication",
  "operatingSystem": "Web Browser",
  "featureList": ["Interactive canvas benchmark"],
  "offers": { "@type": "Offer", "price": "0" }
};
---

<Base title={title} description={description} jsonLd={jsonLd}>
  <div class="bench-page" style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; height: 100vh; background: #0c0c0c; color: #e8e8e8; font-family: 'IBM Plex Mono', monospace;">
    <div class="bench-header" style="height: 48px; border-bottom: 1px solid #222; display: flex; align-items: center; padding: 0 24px; flex-shrink: 0;">
      <a href="/" class="bench-back" style="color: #555; text-decoration: none; margin-right: 16px;">← Back</a>
      <h1 class="bench-title" style="font-size: 13px; font-weight: 600; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.08em; margin: 0;">{title}</h1>
    </div>
    
    <div style="flex-grow: 1; display: flex; flex-direction: column; min-height: 0;">
      <LocalDimming client:load />
    </div>

    <section class="seo-article" style="padding: 32px 24px; max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto; line-height: 1.6; color: #e8e8e8;">
      <h2 style="font-size: 20px; margin-bottom: 16px;">Full Array Local Dimming (FALD) Explained</h2>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 16px;">Full Array Local Dimming (FALD) is a backlight technology used in premium LCD monitors and televisions to improve contrast ratio. Instead of a single uniform backlight behind the entire screen, FALD divides the backlight into dozens or hundreds of independently controllable zones. When a dark scene is displayed, zones behind the dark areas are dimmed or switched off entirely — allowing the panel to achieve near-black levels that are impossible with standard edge-lit LCD designs.</p>
      <h3 style="font-size: 16px; margin: 24px 0 12px; color: #ccc;">Blooming: The FALD Tradeoff</h3>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 16px;">The fundamental limitation of FALD is zone size. Since each dimming zone covers many pixels, a small bright object on a dark background — like a white subtitle on a black cinema scene, or a star in space — forces its entire zone to stay lit. This creates a visible glow or "halo" around the bright object, called blooming. The more dimming zones a panel has, the smaller the halo. Mini-LED displays (like the Apple Pro Display XDR with 576 zones, or the ASUS ROG Swift PG32UQ with 1152 zones) dramatically reduce blooming compared to entry-level FALD panels with just 32 zones.</p>
      <h3 style="font-size: 16px; margin: 24px 0 12px; color: #ccc;">FALD vs OLED vs MiniLED</h3>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 16px;">OLED panels sidestep the blooming problem entirely by making each pixel its own light source — true per-pixel local dimming. This gives OLEDs infinite contrast ratios in theory. MiniLED is a middle ground: using microscopic LEDs to create thousands of dimming zones in an LCD, approaching OLED contrast without the burn-in risk. This test creates the worst-case scenario for local dimming — a small bright white object on a pure black background — so you can evaluate how well your panel handles the blooming challenge.</p>
    </section>
  </div>
</Base>
